	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Would it work?</div>
<br />I'd be willing to bet it does. Most of the PPU's stateful operations are at the per-scanline level. It's just a some address decoding and range checks that are affected by the different settings, and it seems like it would take extra hardware and logic to cache that on a per-frame basis.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>dvdmth</b> [ Tue Mar 20, 2007 6:35 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The worst that can happen with changing sprite sizes mid-frame is that the sprites on the following scanline (the one after the scanline in which the change was made) will be glitched.  This problem should not occur if no sprites are in range on that scanline under 8x16 rules.  You can also prevent the problem altogether by making the change after PPU cycle 320 or before PPU cycle 64 (the time period in which sprite rendering is not operational).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


